{
  "text": "To obtain each infant's phase individuation threshold, a logistic function was fit to the target preference scores as a function of temporal frequency. Because the peak target preference score across both groups of infants was 0.65 at the slowest temporal frequency (0.2 Hz), the upper asymptote (ceiling) of the function was fixed at 0.70, in order to improve the fit to the data [CITATION_1] . The lower limit was set to 0.25 (chance performance). Phase individuation threshold level was thus defined as the temporal frequency yielding half the asymptotic performance, corresponding to a target preference score of 0.475, which is equivalent to using the 75% performance correct threshold level for a typical two-alternative forced-choice task. Higher temporal frequency thresholds indicate greater temporal resolution of attention.",
